D The Military Equipment Directory\"/>\n* {{flag|Moldova}}: 27 BTR-60PB''s'' inherited from the Soviet Union in 1991.<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 5\"/> 161 TAB-71M''s'' ordered in 1992 from Romania and delivered between 1992 and 1995 (the vehicles were previously in Romanian service).<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> Currently 12 BTR-60PB''s'' and 121 TAB-71M''s'' are in service.\n* {{flag|Mongolia}}:<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/> 50 BTR-60PB''s'' were ordered in 1975 from the Soviet Union and delivered between 1975 and 1976.<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> Currently 300 BTR-60''s'' are in service.<ref>army-guide website</ref>\n* {{flag|Morocco}}:<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/> Currently more than 45 are in service.\n* {{flag|Mozambique}}:<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/> 30 BTR-60PB''s'' were ordered in 1977 from the Soviet Union and delivered in 1977 (the vehicles were probably previously in Soviet service). 60 BTR-60PB''s'' were ordered in 1979 from the Soviet Union and delivered between 1981 and 1986 (the vehicles were previously in Soviet service).<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> More than 150 BTR-60''s'' in service in 2001.<ref>[http://www.iss.co.za/Af/profiles/Mozambique/SecInfo.html Mozambique \u2013 Security Information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304224607/http://www.iss.co.za/Af/profiles/Mozambique/SecInfo.html |date=4 March 2009 }}. Iss.co.za. Retrieved on 21 September 2011.</ref> Currently 150 BTR-60''s'' are in service.\n* {{flag|Namibia}}: 10 BTR-60''s'' in service in 2001.<ref>[http://www.iss.co.za/Af/profiles/Namibia/SecInfo.html Namibia \u2013 Security Information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090808173317/http://www.iss.co.za/Af/profiles/Namibia/SecInfo.html |date=8 August 2009 }}. Iss.co.za. Retrieved on 21 September 2011.</ref>\n* {{flag|Nicaragua}}:<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/> 84 BTR-60PB''s'' were ordered in 1981 from the Soviet Union and delivered between 1981 and 1988 (the vehicles were probably previously in Soviet service).<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> Currently 64 BTR-60PB''s'' are in service.\n* {{flag|Nigeria}}: Currently 6 are in service.\n* {{flag|North Korea}}:<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/> 100 BTR-60PB''s'' were ordered in 1973 from the Soviet Union and delivered between 1974 and 1975.<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> There were 1,010 [[Korshun]]''s'', [[VTT-323]]''s'', [[Type 63 (armoured personnel carrier)|Type 63]]''s'' (YW-531), [[BTR-40]]''s'', [[BTR-50]]''s'', BTR-60''s'' and [[BTR-152]]''s'' in service in 1985, 2,200 VTT-323''s'', Type 63''s'' (YW-531), BTR-40''s'', BTR-50''s'', BTR-60''s'' and BTR-152''s'' in service in 1990 and 1995 and 2,500 VTT-323''s'', Type 63''s'' (YW-531), BTR-40''s'', BTR-50''s'', BTR-60''s'' and BTR-152''s'' in service in 2000, 2002 and 2005.<ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/dprk/kpa-equipment.htm Equipment Holdings \u2013 Korean People's Army] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141123011853/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/dprk/kpa-equipment.htm |date=23 November 2014 }} globalsecurity.org</ref> Currently 1,000 BTR-60''s'' are in service.\n* {{flag|North Macedonia}}: Currently 35 are in service.\n* {{flag|Peru}}: Currently 12 are in service.\n* {{flag|Romania}}: Produced 1,872 TAB-71''s'', TAB-71M''s'', TERA-71''s'', TERA-71L''s'', TAB-71A R-1450''s'', TAB-71A R-1451''s'', TAB-71A R-1452''s'' and 491 TAB-71AR''s'' between 1970 and 1990 for the Romanian army. More were produced for export.<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> Currently 965 TAB-71''s'', TERA-71''s'', TERA-71L''s'', TAB-71A R-1450''s'', TAB-71A R-1451''s'', TAB-71A R-1452''s'' and 491 TAB-71AR''s'' are in service.<ref>[http://armyreco.ifrance.com/europe/roumanie/roumanie_index_materiel.htm Romanian army] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091223103022/http://armyreco.ifrance.com/europe/roumanie/roumanie_index_materiel.htm |date=23 December 2009 }} armyrecognition.com</ref>\n* {{flag|Russia}}: There were 4,900 BTR-60''s'', [[BTR-70]]''s'' and [[BTR-80]]''s'' in service in 2002 and 2003 including 750 in service with the Naval infantry and 280 in service the coastal defense forces.<ref>[http://www.warfare.ru/?catid=239&linkid=1557 Russian Armed Forces: 1999 -2003. 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716082343/http://warfare.ru/?catid=239&linkid=1557 |date=16 July 2011 }}. Warfare.ru. Retrieved on 21 September 2011.</ref> 6,000 [[BTR-50]]''s'', BTR-60''s'', BTR-70''s'', BTR-80''s'' and [[BTR-152]]''s'' in service in 2000, 2005 and 2008.<ref name=\"Soviet/Russian Army equipment\">[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/russia/army-equipment.htm Soviet/Russian Army equipment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120626123431/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/russia/army-equipment.htm |date=26 June 2012 }}. Globalsecurity.org. Retrieved on 21 September 2011.</ref> Currently 17 are in active service and some are kept in storage.<ref>[http://www.warfare.ru/?catid=245&linkid=2296 BTR-60] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718134346/http://www.warfare.ru/?catid=245&linkid=2296 |date=18 July 2011 }}. Warfare.ru. Retrieved on 21 September 2011.</ref>\n* {{flag|Rwanda}}<ref>[http://www.armyrecognition.com/rwanda_rwandan_army_uk/rwanda_rwandan_army_land_ground_forces_military_equipment_armoured_vehicle_pictures_information_desc.html Ruandan army] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090209062159/http://www.armyrecognition.com/rwanda_rwandan_army_uk/rwanda_rwandan_army_land_ground_forces_military_equipment_armoured_vehicle_pictures_information_desc.html |date=9 February 2009 }} armyrecognition.com</ref>\n* {{SADR|Polisario}}<ref>[http://personal5.iddeo.es/jesusm1/fpolisario.html Frente Polisario] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615073540/http://personal5.iddeo.es/jesusm1/fpolisario.html |date=15 June 2007 }}</ref>\n[[File:BTR-60PB DA-ST-89-06597.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A [[Somali Armed Forces|Somali National Army]] BTR-60 armoured personnel carrier.]]\n* {{flag|Serbia}}: 60\n* {{flag|Somalia}}:<ref name=\"JED The Military Equipment Directory\"/> 10 BTR-60PB''s'' were ordered in 1976 from the Soviet Union and delivered in 1976.<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> 5 are currently in service.\n* {{flag|Sudan}}<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/>\n* {{flag|Syria}}:<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/><ref name=\"JED The Military Equipment Directory\"/> 150 BTR-60PB''s'' were ordered in 1970 from the Soviet Union and delivered between 1970 and 1971. 500 BTR-60PB''s'' were ordered in 1973 from the Soviet Union and delivered between 1973 and 1975.<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> Around 1,500 BTR-40''s'', BTR-50''s'', BTR-60PB''s'', [[BTR-152]]''s'' and [[OT-64]]''s'' in service in 1990, 1995 and 2000 and around 1,600 in 2001, 2003 and 2005.<ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/syria/army-equipment.htm Syria \u2013 Army Equipment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017132707/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/syria/army-equipment.htm |date=17 October 2014 }}. Globalsecurity.org. Retrieved on 21 September 2011.</ref> 600 BTR-60PB''s'' are currently in service.\n* {{flag|Tajikistan}}: 7 were inherited from Soviet Union. 1 in service in 2000 and 2005.<ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/centralasia/tajik-army-equipment.htm Tajik-Army Equipment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150430002305/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/centralasia/tajik-army-equipment.htm |date=30 April 2015 }}. Globalsecurity.org. Retrieved on 21 September 2011.</ref>\n* {{flag|Turkmenistan}}: There were 543 BTR-60''s'', [[BTR-70]]''s'' and [[BTR-80]]''s'' in service in 1995 and 829 in 2000 and 2005.<ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/centralasia/turkmen-army-equipment.htm Turkmen-Army Equipment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150429232138/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/centralasia/turkmen-army-equipment.htm |date=29 April 2015 }}. Globalsecurity.org. Retrieved on 21 September 2011.</ref>\n* {{flag|Transnistria}}<ref>{{cite web |author=Tiraspol Hostel |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FC6kMKmV3VM |title=Transnistria Army Tanks in center of Tiraspol! |publisher=Tiraspol Hostel |date=2014-04-13 |accessdate=2017-08-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180526164351/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FC6kMKmV3VM |archive-date=26 May 2018 |url-status=live |language=it}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Uganda}}: 20 BTR-60''s'' in service in 1999.<ref>[http://www.iss.co.za/AF/profiles/uganda/SecInfo.html Uganda \u2013 Security Information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506074521/http://www.iss.co.za/af/profiles/Uganda/SecInfo.html |date=6 May 2009 }}. Iss.co.za. Retrieved on 21 September 2011.</ref>\n* {{flag|Ukraine}}: 500<ref>[http://www.armyrecognition.com/ukraine_uk/ukraine_ukrainian_army_land_ground_forces_military_equipment_armoured_vehicle_pictures_information_d.html Ukrainian army] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091003225109/http://www.armyrecognition.com/ukraine_uk/ukraine_ukrainian_army_land_ground_forces_military_equipment_armoured_vehicle_pictures_information_d.html |date=3 October 2009 }} armyrecognition.com</ref> were inherited from the Soviet Union. 220 in service in 1995, 202 in 2000 and 176 in 2005.<ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/ukraine/groundforces-equipment.htm Ground Forces Equipment \u2013 Ukraine] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707104146/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/ukraine/groundforces-equipment.htm |date=7 July 2017 }}. Globalsecurity.org. Retrieved on 21 September 2011.</ref>\n* {{flag|Uzbekistan}}: There were 24 in service in 2000 and 2005.<ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/centralasia/uzbek-army-equipment.htm Uzbek-Army Equipment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006125425/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/centralasia/uzbek-army-equipment.htm |date=6 October 2014 }}. Globalsecurity.org. Retrieved on 21 September 2011.</ref> Currently 24 are in service.\n* {{flag|Vietnam}}:<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/> 500 BTR-60PB''s'' were ordered in 1978 from the Soviet Union and delivered between 1978 and 1980 (the vehicles were probably previously in Soviet service).<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> Currently 400 BTR-60''s'' are in service.\n* {{flag|Yemen}}:<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/> Currently 500 are in service.\n* {{flag|Zambia}}:<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/> 13 BTR-60PB''s'' were ordered in 1979 from the Soviet Union and delivered in 1980 (the vehicles were probably previously in Soviet service, part of the deal worth between $72 million and $100 million).<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> Currently 13 are in service.\n\n===Former operators===\n* {{flag|Czechoslovakia}}:<ref name=\"Pancerni 1\"/> 28 BTR-60PU-12s were ordered along with 28 [[9K31]] SAM batteries in 1979 from the Soviet Union and delivered between 1980 and 1989. 5 BTR-60PU-12s were ordered in 1982 from the Soviet Union and delivered between 1982 and 1984 (used in 5 [[9K33]]M Osa-M SAM batteries). 25 BTR-60PU-12s were ordered in 1984 from the Soviet Union and delivered between 1984 and 1990 (used in 25 [[9K35 Strela-10]] SAM batteries).<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/>\n* {{flag|East Germany}}:<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/> 1,500 SPW-60Ps, SPW-60PAs and SPW-60PBs were ordered in 1963 from the Soviet Union and delivered between 1965 and 1970. 24 BTR-60PU-12s were ordered along with 24 [[9K31]] SAM batteries in 1978 from the Soviet Union and delivered between 1979 and 1984.<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> 260 SPW-60PAs and 2,000 SPW-60PBs (including variants) were passed on to the unified German state.\n* {{flag|Finland}}:<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/><ref name=\"JED The Military Equipment Directory\"/> 120 BTR-60PBs were ordered in 1975 from the Soviet Union and delivered in 1976.<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> Withdrawn from service in 2006.\n* {{flag|Germany}}: 260 SPW-60PA and 2,000 SPW-60PB (including variants), taken from GDR's army; all scrapped or sold to other countries.\n* {{flag|Georgia}}: 3 BTR-60s and BTR-70s used in [[War in Abkhazia (1992\u20131993)]].<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 5\"/> 1 BTR-60 in service in 2005 and 2008.<ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/georgia/army-equipment.htm Georgia Army] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100311235243/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/georgia/army-equipment.htm |date=11 March 2010 }}. Globalsecurity.org. Retrieved on 21 September 2011.</ref>\n* {{flag|Grenada}}: 6 BTR-60PBs were ordered in 1981 from the Soviet Union and delivered in 1982 (the vehicles were probably previously in Soviet service).<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> \n* {{flagcountry|Ba'athist Iraq}}: 250 BTR-60PBs were ordered in 1970 from the Soviet Union and delivered between 1971 and 1975.<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> At peak there were 500 BTR-60s in service. There were 3,500 [[BTR-50]]s, BTR-60s, [[BTR-152]]s, [[EE-11 Urutu]]s, [[Panhard M3]]s, [[M113A1]]s, M113A2s, [[OT-62 TOPAS]]ess, [[OT-64 SKOT]]s and [[Walid]]s in service in 1990, around 2,000 BTR-50s, BTR-60s, BTR-152s, EE-11 Urutus, Panhard M3s, [[MT-LB]]s, OT-62 TOPASes, OT-64 SKOTs, Walids and [[YW-701]]s in 1995, around 2,400 BTR-50s, BTR-60s, BTR-152s, EE-11 Urutus, Panhard M3s, MT-LBs, OT-62 TOPASes, OT-64 SKOTs, Walids and [[YW-701]]s in 2000 and around 2,400 BTR-50s, BTR-60s, BTR-152s, EE-11 Urutus, Panhard M3s, MT-LBs, M113A1s, M113A2s, OT-62 TOPASes, OT-64 SKOTs, Walids and [[YW-701]]s in 2002.<ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/iraq/ground-equipment.htm Iraqi Ground Forces Equipment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005040522/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/iraq/ground-equipment.htm |date=5 October 2013 }} globalsecurity.org</ref>\n* {{flag|Lebanon}}: 18 BTR-60PBs delivered by Iraq to the [[Lebanese Forces (militia)|Lebanese Forces]] in 1988. 10 BTR-60PBs delivered by [[Israel]] to the [[South Lebanon Army]] in 1982. Unknown number of vehicles delivered by Syria to the [[Druze in Lebanon|Druze]] [[People's Liberation Army (Lebanon)|People's Liberation Army]] militia in 1983.<ref>Kassis, ''30 Years of Military Vehicles in Lebanon'' (2003), p. 58.</ref>\n* {{flag|Poland}}:<ref name=\"JED The Military Equipment Directory\"/> Several BTRs were used by the People's Army of Poland, but were not accepted in armaments because of the competing Polish-Czech [[OT-64 SKOT]], so they were sold to ZOMO. In 1981\u20131982, 40 transporters were delivered in the PB version for ZOMO and the [[Milicja Obywatelska]]. After 1989 they were sent to the [[Policja]], where they are withdrawn for the moment, or are in stock. Some have been handed over to museums.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pomorska.pl/wiadomosci/bydgoszcz/art/6439526,dwa-transportery-opancerzone-btr-60-pb-dotarly-do-muzeum-wojsk-ladowych-przekazala-je-bydgoska-policja,id,t.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829220131/http://www.pomorska.pl/wiadomosci/bydgoszcz/art/6439526,dwa-transportery-opancerzone-btr-60-pb-dotarly-do-muzeum-wojsk-ladowych-przekazala-je-bydgoska-policja,id,t.html |archive-date=29 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Soviet Union}}: Produced around 25,000 BTR-60s.<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/> 35,500 [[BTR-50]]s, BTR-60s, BTR-70s, BTR-80s and [[BTR-152]]s in service in 1985.<ref name=\"Soviet/Russian Army equipment\"/> 4,191 BTR-60s in service with units station in the European part of Soviet Union in 1990.<ref name=\"Otechestvennye koljosnye bronetransportjory BTR-60, BTR-70, BTR-80 p. 27\"/> Passed on to successor states.\n* {{flag|North Yemen}}: 150 BTR-60PBs were ordered in 1979 from the Soviet Union and delivered in 1980 (the vehicles were probably previously in Soviet service).<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/>\n* {{flag|South Yemen}}: 100 BTR-60PBs were ordered in 1981 from the Soviet Union and delivered between 1981 and 1982 (the vehicles were probably previously in Soviet service). 40 BTR-60PBs were ordered in 1986 from the Soviet Union and delivered in 1986 (the vehicles were probably previously in Soviet service).<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/>\n* {{flag|Turkey}}:<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/><ref name=\"JED The Military Equipment Directory\"/> 300 SPW-60PB''s'' were ordered in 1990 from Germany with 195 being delivered between 1990 and 1991 and 105 being delivered in 1992 (the vehicles were previously in East German service, part of the CFE Cascade programme).<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/><ref name=\"Pancerni 2\"/><ref name=\"Deagel\"/> 23 BTR-60PB''s'' were ordered in 1993 from Russia and delivered in 1993 (the vehicles were previously in Soviet and later Russian service, part of a $75M deal, used by the police).<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> All now phased out of [[Turkish Armed Forces]] service ,used only by [[Gendarmerie General Command]]. \n* {{flag|Yugoslavia}}: 80 BTR-60Ps were ordered in 1965 from the Soviet Union and delivered in 1966. 40 TAB-71s were ordered in 1978 from Romania and delivered between 1980 and 1981 (used by the police).<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 4\"/><ref name=\"SIPRI\"/>\n* {{flag|Zaire}}: 10 BTR-60PBs were ordered in 1980 from an unknown supplier and delivered in 1980 (the vehicles were probably second-hand).<ref name=\"SIPRI\"/> Passed on to the successor state.\n\n==See also==\n* [[OT-64 SKOT]] \u2013 Polish/Czechoslovak equivalent to the Soviet BTR-60\n* [[BTR-70]] \u2013 Successor to the BTR-60\n* [[BTR-80]]\n* [[BTR-90]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* Hull, A.W., Markov, D.R., Zaloga, S.J. (1999) ''Soviet/Russian Armor and Artillery Design Practices 1945 to Present''. Darlington Productions. {{ISBN|1-892848-01-5}}.\n* A.V. Karpenko (1996) ''Obozreniye Bronetankovoj Tekhniki (1905\u20131995 gg.)'' Nevskij Bastion\n* Samer Kassis, ''30 Years of Military Vehicles in Lebanon'', Beirut: Elite Group, 2003. {{ISBN|9953-0-0705-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n*[http://www.armyrecognition.com/Russe/vehicules_a_roues/BTR-60/BTR60_Russie_description.htm Data sheet and pictures BTR-60PB ArmyRecognition.com]\n*[https://fas.org/man/dod-101/sys/land/row/btr-60.htm Fas.org]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070219002415/http://armoured.vif2.ru/btr60.htm Description (in russian) and photo gallery at armoured.vif2.ru]\n*[http://freenet-homepage.de/SASundChiffrierdienst/trupps.html P-238xx, P-240xx, P-241xx, P-242xx, P-244xx]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100120131249/http://walkarounds.airforce.ru/armour/rus/btr-60pb/index.htm BTR-60PB walkaround]\n*[http://www.dishmodels.ru/wshow.htm?p=1768 BTR-60PA walkaround]\n\n{{Modern IFV and APC}}\n{{PostWWIISovietAFVS|APC}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Btr-60}}\n[[Category:Armoured personnel carriers of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Armoured fighting vehicles of Romania]]\n[[Category:Armoured personnel carriers of the Cold War]]\n[[Category:Cold War armoured fighting vehicles of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Command vehicles]]\n[[Category:Amphibious armoured personnel carriers]]\n[[Category:Wheeled amphibious armoured fighting vehicles]]\n[[Category:GAZ Group military vehicles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n|name= BTR-60\n| image= BTR-60PB NVA.JPG\n| image_size = 300\n|caption= A BTR-60PB\n|origin= [[Soviet Union]]\n|type=Wheeled [[Amphibious warfare|amphibious]] [[armored personnel carrier]]\n|is_vehicle=yes\n|service= 1959\u2013present\n|used_by=See [[BTR-60#Operators|Operators]]\n|wars=See [[BTR-60#List of conflicts|List of conflicts]]\n|designer=V. A. Dedkov\n|design_date=1955<ref name=\"Pancerni 1\"/>\n|manufacturer=[[Gorkovsky Avtomobilny Zavod]] (Soviet Union)<br/> [[Ratmil Regie Autonoma]] (Romania, TAB-71)\n|production_date=1960\u20131976 (Soviet Union)<ref name=\"Czo\u0142gi \u015awiata 1\"/>\n|number=~25,000 (Soviet Union)<ref name=\"Czo