rom the first day of the 2018 season until the day before the first day of the 2019 season. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Team\n!Former<br />coach\n!Interim<br />coach\n!New<br />coach\n!Reason\n|-\n| [[Abilene Christian Wildcats baseball|Abilene Christian]]\n| [[Britt Bonneau]]\n|\n| [[Rick McCarty]]\n| Bonneau resigned from Abeline Christian on May 19 after 22 seasons. On June 12, the Wildcats hired former [[Dallas Baptist Patriots|Dallas Baptist]] pitching coach McCarty for the head coaching job.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bigcountryhomepage.com/sports/mccarty-is-new-acu-baseball-coach/1234304718 |title=McCarty is new ACU baseball coach |author=David Robinett |date=June 12, 2018 |publisher=Nexstar Broadcasting, Inc. |work=www.bigcountryhomepage.com |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Alabama A&M Bulldogs|Alabama A&M]]\n| [[Mitch Hill]]\n|\n| [[Manny Lora]]\n| Hill resigned from Alabama A&M on June 25 after 5 seasons for the head coaching job at [[Martin Methodist College]] of the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2018/06/alabama_am_baseball_coach_mitc.html |title=Alabama A&M baseball coach Mitch Hill resigns after 5 seasons |author=Daniel Boyette |date=June 25, 2018 |publisher=Advance Local Media LLC |work=www.al.com |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> Pitching coach and recruiting coordinator Lora was promoted to head coach of the Bulldogs on August 23.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.al.com/aam/index.ssf/2018/08/alabama_am_promotes_manny_lora.html |title=Alabama A&M promotes Manny Lora to head baseball coach |date=August 23, 2018 |publisher=Advance Local Media LLC. |work=www.al.com |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Central Michigan Chippewas baseball|Central Michigan]]\n| [[Steve Jaska]]\n|\n| [[Jordan Bischel]]\n| Jaska announced his retirement after 16 seasons at Central Michigan on June 2.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/sports/college/2018/06/02/college-notes-cmus-winningest-baseball-coach-steve-jaksa-retires/666585002/|title=College notes: CMU's 2nd-winningest baseball coach retires|work=[[The Detroit News]]|first=Tony|last=Paul|date=June 2, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> On June 28, the Chippewas hired Bischel from [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] [[Northwood Timberwolves|Northwood]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ourmidland.com/sports/article/Baseball-coach-Bischel-leaving-Northwood-for-CMU-13032258.php |title=Baseball coach Bischel leaving Northwood for CMU |author=Fred Kelly |date=June 28, 2018 |publisher=Midland Daily News |work=www.ourmidland.com |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Davidson Wildcats baseball|Davidson]]\n| [[Dick Cooke]]\n|\n| [[Rucker Taylor]]\n| Cooke announced on February 12 that he will step down following the 2018 season with associate head coach Rucker succeeding him.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collegebaseballdaily.com/2018/02/12/davidsons-names-rucker-taylor-as-head-coach-after-2018-season/ |title=Davidson's names Rucker Taylor as head coach after 2018 season |author=Brian Foley |date=February 12, 2018 |publisher=PenciDesign |work=www.collegebaseballdaily.com |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Fairleigh Dickinson Knights|Fairleigh Dickinson]]\n| [[Gary Puccio]]\n| [[Justin McKay]]\n|\n| Puccio announced his retirement after 8 seasons at FDU and 27 seasons overall, effective May 15. Assistant coach McKay will serve as the interim head coach of the Knights for the 2019 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fduknights.com/news/2018/5/30/justin-mckay-named-interim-head-baseball-coach.aspx |title=Justin McKay Named Interim Head Baseball Coach |date=May 30, 2018 |publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson University |work=www.fduknights.com |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Illinois State Redbirds baseball|Illinois State]]\n| [[Bo Durkac]]\n|\n| [[Steve Holm]]\n| Durkac was fired on May 29 after 4 seasons at Illinois State, finishing 82-134 overall and 27-55 in conference play.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pjstar.com/sports/20180529/illinois-state-fires-baseball-coach-bo-durkac|title=Illinois State fires baseball coach Bo Durkac|work=[[The Daily Star-Journal]]|date=May 29, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> On June 22, the Redbirds hired Purdue pitching coach Holm for the head coaching job.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pantagraph.com/sports/college/illinois-state/isu-names-holm-as-new-baseball-coach/article_3afa3f58-9c93-5cfd-9777-e8f41e94fc64.html|title=ISU names Holm as new baseball coach|last=Reinhardt|first=Randy|work=pantagraph.com|access-date=2018-11-15|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Indiana Hoosiers baseball|Indiana]]\n| [[Chris Lemonis]]\n|\n| [[Jeff Mercer]]\n| Lemonis left after 4 seasons at Indiana to take the Mississippi State job.<ref name=Lemonis>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/23907293/mississippi-state-bulldogs-hire-chris-lemonis-baseball-coach|title=Mississippi State hires Chris Lemonis as new baseball coach |website=ESPN |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref> The school hired Wright State head coach Jeff Mercer on July 2.<ref name=Mercer>{{cite news|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/college/indiana/2018/07/02/iu-baseball-tabs-bargersville-native-jeff-mercer-head-coach/753281002/|title=IU baseball tabs Bargersville native Jeff Mercer as head coach|accessdate=July 2, 2018|newspaper=[[The Indianapolis Star]]}}</ref>  \n|-\n| [[Iona Gaels baseball|Iona]]\n| [[Pat Carey]]\n|\n| [[Paul Panik]]\n| On May 15 it was announced that Pat Carey will not return to the team for the 2019 season after thirteen years with the school. The school hired Albany assistant Paul Panik on June 25.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Beyrer |first1=Brian |title=Senior Associated Athletic Director - Athletic Communications |url=https://icgaels.com/news/2018/6/25/paul-panik-named-head-baseball-coach.aspx |website=Iona Gaels |publisher=Iona Gaels |accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Kansas State Wildcats baseball|Kansas State]]\n| [[Brad Hill (baseball coach)|Brad Hill]]\n| \n| [[Pete Hughes]]\n| Brad Hill Announced that on May 8 after fifteen seasons that he will step down affective at the end of the season. He became the team's all time most successful coach and won the 2013 Big 12 Conference title and hosted a super regional that year. On June 8, the Wildcats hired former Boston College, Virginia Tech, and Oklahoma head coach Pete Hughes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Allen |first=Deaundra |url=http://www.kansascity.com/sports/college/big-12/kansas-state/article212813579.html |title=K-State hires former OU, Virginia Tech coach to lead baseball program |date=June 8, 2018 |accessdate=June 8, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Miami Hurricanes baseball|Miami (FL)]]\n| [[Jim Morris (baseball coach)|Jim Morris]]\n| \n| [[Gino DiMare]]\n| Morris announced in June 2014 that he would retire after the 2018 season, and that DiMare would take over as head coach at that time.\n|-\n| [[Middle Tennessee Blue Raiders|Middle Tennessee]]\n| [[Jim McGuire (baseball coach)|Jim McGuire]]\n|\n| [[Jim Toman]]\n| McGuire was fired on May 21 after 6 seasons at Middle Tennessee.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nashvillepost.com/sports/area-colleges/blog/21005904/mtsu-fires-baseball-coach-jim-mcguire|title=MTSU fires baseball coach Jim McGuire|work=[[Nashville Post]]|first=David|last=Boclair|date=May 21, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> On June 20, the Blue Raiders hired Charleston associate head coach and former Liberty head coach Toman for the job.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dnj.com/story/sports/college/mtsu/2018/06/20/mtsu-baseball-jim-toman-takes-over-blue-raider-program/715775002/ |title=Jim Toman, former College of Charleston assistant and recruiter, named MTSU baseball coach |author=Cecil Joyce |date=June 20, 2018 |publisher=Daily News Journal |work=www.dnj.com |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Mississippi State Bulldogs baseball|Mississippi State]]\n| [[Andy Cannizaro]]\n| [[Gary Henderson (baseball coach)|Gary Henderson]]\n| [[Chris Lemonis]]\n| Cannizaro resigned on February 22, only three games into the Bulldogs' season, after he was found to be involved in an extramarital affair with a woman working in MSU's athletic department. Former [[Kentucky Wildcats baseball|Kentucky]] head coach and current MSU pitching coach Henderson was named as interim replacement.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/story/_/id/22544998/sources-say-mississippi-state-baseball-coach-andy-cannizaro-abruptly-resigned-due-extramarital-affair |title=Sources: Mississippi State's Andy Cannizaro resigned due to affair |website=ESPN.com |date=February 22, 2018 |accessdate=March 4, 2018}}</ref> MSU announced the hiring of Indiana head coach Chris Lemonis on June 26.<ref name=Lemonis/>\n|-\n| [[Murray State Racers|Murray State]]\n| [[Kevin Moulder]]\n|\n| [[Dan Skirka]]\n| Murray State announced on May 25 that Moulder would not return next season, ending his 4-year tenure at the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thenews.org/2018/05/25/moulder-ousted-following-four-losing-seasons/|title=Moulder ousted following four losing seasons|website=thenews.org|first=Gage|last=Johnson|date=May 25, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> On July 2, the school hired former Racer assistant coach Skirka to be the new head coach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.paducahsun.com/sports/general/skirka-introduced-as-msu-baseball-coach/article_9cdabf22-adca-5ed4-8128-f8b8410af570.html |title=Skirka introduced as MSU baseball coach |author=Edward Marlowe |date=July 2, 2018 |publisher=BLOX Content Management System |work=www.paducahsun.com |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Oregon State Beavers baseball|Oregon State]]\n| [[Pat Casey (baseball)|Pat Casey]] \n| [[Pat Bailey]]\n|\n| Casey announced his retirement on September 6 after 24 seasons at Oregon State and 30 seasons overall, winning 900 games with the Beavers and 3 NCAA championships. Associate head coach Bailey will serve as the interim head coach of the team for the 2019 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/beavers/index.ssf/2018/09/pat_casey_oregon_state_beavers_1.html |title=Pat Casey, Oregon State Beavers baseball coach, announces retirement |author=Joel Odom |date=September 6, 2018 |publisher=Advance Local Media LLC |work=www.oregonlive.com |accessdate=November 11, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Pittsburgh Panthers baseball|Pittsburgh]]\n| [[Joe Jordano]]\n|\n| [[Mike Bell (baseball coach)|Mike Bell]]\n| Jordano resigned from Pittsburgh on June 22 after 21 seasons at the helm. On July 10, former Florida State pitching coach Bell was named head coach of the Panthers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/sports/Pitt/2018/07/10/mike-bell-pitt-baseball-coach-pittsburgh-florida-state-heather-lyke-joe-jordano/stories/201807100155 |title=Mike Bell, ex-Florida State assistant, is Pitt's new baseball coach |author=Brian Batko |date=July 10, 2018 |publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |work=www.post-gazette.com |accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Rice Owls baseball|Rice]]\n| [[Wayne Graham]]\n| \n| [[Matt Bragga]]\n| Graham, who was the oldest head coach in Division I baseball at age 82, announced on April 25 that his contract was not being renewed and that the 2018 season would be the last of his 27-year head coaching tenure at Rice.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/baseball/story/_/id/23316561/wayne-graham-says-2018-season-last-rice |title=Baseball coach Wayne Graham says this is his last year at Rice |agency=Associated Press |website=ESPN.com |date=April 25, 2018 |accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref> The Owls hired Tennessee Tech head coach Bragga after the season.<ref name=\"Bragga to Rice\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/story/_/id/23811151/rice-owls-hire-matt-bragga-replace-wayne-graham-baseball-coach |title=Rice Owls hire Matt Bragga to succeed Wayne Graham |website=ESPN.com |date=June 16, 2018|accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Tennessee Tech Golden Eagles baseball|Tennessee Tech]]\n| [[Matt Bragga]]\n| \n| [[Justin Holmes]]\n| Bragga left after 15 seasons at Tennessee Tech to take the Rice job.<ref name=\"Bragga to Rice\"/>  The school promoted assistant coach and recruiting coordinator Justin Holmes on June 21.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/2018/06/21/tennessee-tech-promotes-justin-holmes-head-baseball-coach-college-world-series-matt-bragga-rice/720918002/ |title=Tennessee Tech promotes Justin Holmes to head baseball coach |author=Mike Organ |date=June 21, 2018 |publisher=Tennessean |work=www.Tennessean.com |accessdate=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[UC Irvine Anteaters baseball|UC Irvine]]\n| [[Mike Gillespie (baseball coach)|Mike Gillespie]]\n| \n| [[Ben Orloff]]\n| Mike Gillespie announced his retirement from the UC Irvine baseball team after eleven seasons with the school his successor Ben Orloff was named his replacement beginning in the 2019 season. He became the most successful coach in College baseball history with 1108 wins.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ocregister.com/2018/05/18/uc-irvine-celebrates-retiring-coach-mike-gillespie-with-pregame-ceremony-jersey-honor/|title=UC Irvine Celebrates Retiring Coach Mike Gillespie With Pregame Ceremony Jersey Honor|website=OCRegister.com|date=May 18, 2018|accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Wright State Raiders baseball|Wright State]]\n| [[Jeff Mercer]]\n|\n| [[Alex Sogard]]\n| Mercer left after 2 seasons at Wright State to take the Indiana job.<ref name=Mercer/> The school promoted assistant coach Alex Sogard on July 6.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wright State's Alex Sogard promoted to head baseball coach |url=https://webapp2.wright.edu/web1/newsroom/2018/07/06/wright-states-alex-sogard-promoted-to-head-baseball-coach/ |website=Wright State Athletics |publisher=Wright State Media Team |accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{NCAA Division I baseball season navbox|state=autocollapse}}\n\n[[Category:2018 NCAA Division I baseball season|2018 NCAA Division I baseball season]]\n", "text_old": "{{College baseball season\n| title                  = 2018 NCAA Division I baseball season\n| duration               = February 12 \u2013 June&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2018\n| no_of_games            =  \n| no_of_teams            = 299\n| preseason1             = [[2018 Florida Gators baseball team|Florida]] (Unanimous)\n| DefendingChampions     = [[Florida Gators baseball|Florida]]\n| attendance             =\n| average_attendance     =\n| TV                     = [[ESPN]]\n| tournament_link        = 2018 NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament\n| tournament             = Tournament\n| TourneyDuration        = June 1\u201328, 2018\n| ConferenceBids         = [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] (10)\n| WorldSeries_Link       = 2018 College World Series\n| WorldSeries            = College World Series\n| WorldSeries_champ      = [[2018 Oregon State Beavers baseball team|Oregon State]]\n| WorldSeries_titlecount = 3rd\n| WorldSeries_runner-up  = [[2018 Arkansas Razorbacks baseball team|Arkansas]]\n| WorldSeries_count      = 9th\n| WorldSeries_coach      = [[Pat Casey (baseball)|Pat Casey]]\n| WorldSeries_coachcount = 3rd\n| WorldSeries_MOP        = [[Adley Rutschman]]\n| MOPTeam                = [[Oregon State Beavers baseball|Oregon State]]\n| prevseason_year        = [[2017 NCAA Division I baseball season|2017]]\n| nextseason_year        = [[2019 NCAA Division I baseball season|2019]]\n}}\nThe '''2018 NCAA Division I Baseball season,''' play of [[college baseball]] in the United States organized by the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) at the [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] level, began in February 2018. The season progressed through the regular season, many conference tournaments and championship series, and concluded with the [[2018 NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament]] and [[2018 College World Series]]. The College World Series, consisting of the eight remaining teams in the NCAA Tournament and held annually in [[Omaha, Nebraska]] at [[TD Ameritrade Park Omaha]], ended on June 28, 2018.\n\n==Realignment and format changes==\n* [[NYIT Bears|NYIT]], previously the last remaining Division I independent, moved its baseball program to its full-time home of the [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] [[East Coast Conference]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://nyitbears.com/sports/bsb/2016-17/releases/20170505cr6tli |title=Baseball program to join East Coast Conference for 2017-2018 academic year |publisher=NYIT Bears |date=May 5, 2017 |accessdate=February 24, 2018 }}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* [[Buffalo Bulls baseball|Buffalo]] dropped their baseball program at the end of the 2017 season, leaving the Mid-American Conference with 10 teams. As a result, the MAC dissolved its divisions.\n* The [[Ivy League]] dissolved its divisions, playing in a single league table for the first time since 1992.  The top two finishers will meet in the Championship Series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ivyleague.com/news/2018/2/23/ivies-set-to-commence-2018-baseball-campaign.aspx?path=baseball|publisher=Ivy League|title=Ivies set to Commence 2018 Baseball Campaign|date=February 23, 2018|accessdate=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Wichita State Shockers baseball|Wichita State]] left the [[Missouri Valley Conference]] for the [[American Athletic Conference]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theamerican.org/news/2017/4/7/GEN_0407172824.aspx|title=Wichita State to become a member of the American Athletic Conference|publisher=American Athletic Conference|date=April 7, 2017|accessdate=April 7, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Valparaiso Crusaders baseball|Valparaiso]] left the [[Horizon League]] for the [[Missouri Valley Conference]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mvc-sports.com/baseball/news/2016\u201317/9590/its-official-welcome-valparaiso/|title=It's Official. Welcome, Valparaiso|publisher=Missouri Valley Conference|date=May 25, 2017|accessdate=May 26, 2017}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe 2018 season was also the last for two other teams in their then-current conferences. Both teams moved between the same two conferences, but in opposite directions.\n* [[Liberty Flames baseball|Liberty]], after 27 seasons in the [[Big South Conference]], joined the [[Atlantic Sun Conference]] (ASUN) on July 1, 2018.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://asunsports.org/general/2017-18/releases/20180516hf2r4k |title=ASUN Conference Announces Liberty University as League Member for 2018-19 |publisher=ASUN Conference |date=May 17, 2018 |accessdate=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[USC Upstate Spartans baseball|USC Upstate]], after 11 years in the ASUN, moved to the Big South.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://bigsouthsports.com/news/2017/11/15/general-big-south-to-add-usc-upstate-as-full-member.aspx |title=Big South to add USC Upstate as Full Member |publisher=Big South Conference |date=November 15, 2017 |accessdate=November 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFinally, one other Division I team changed its institutional and athletic identities immediately after the 2017\u201318 season. [[Indiana University]] and [[Purdue University system|Purdue University]] dissolved [[Indiana University \u2013 Purdue University Fort Wayne]] (IPFW) on July 1, 2018. IPFW's academic programs in health sciences transferred to the IU system as [[Indiana University Fort Wayne]]; all remaining academic programs were transferred to the Purdue system as [[Purdue University Fort Wayne]] (PFW). From 2018\u201319, the former IPFW athletic program represents only PFW, and its [[Summit League]] membership was assumed by PFW. Shortly before the dissolution took effect, but after the school's baseball season had finished, the athletic program announced that it would henceforth be known as the [[Purdue Fort Wayne Mastodons baseball|Purdue Fort Wayne Mastodons]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wowo.com/indiana-purdue-trustees-officially-finalize-ipfw-split/ |title=Indiana, Purdue trustees officially finalize IPFW split |first=Darrin |last=Wright |publisher=[[WOWO (AM)|WOWO]] |location=[[Fort Wayne, Indiana|Fort Wayne, IN]] |date=June 16, 2017 |accessdate=January 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.ipfw.edu/about/future/faq.html |title=Frequently Asked Questions/Additional Questions |publisher=Indiana University\u2013Purdue University Fort Wayne |accessdate=January 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204114558/http://www.ipfw.edu/about/future/faq.html |archive-date=2017-12-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.gomastodons.com/news/2018/6/18/general-purdue-fort-wayne-branding-released.aspx |title=Purdue Fort Wayne Branding Released |publisher=Purdue University Fort Wayne |date=June 18, 2018 |accessdate=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===NCAA Tournament===\nFor the first time, the [[2018 NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament]] seeded the top 16 teams, rather than only the top 8 teams as had been the practice since 1999.  This ensures that the regional featuring the top-seeded team is paired with the regional hosted by the 16th-seeded team, where in the past Super Regionals were paired generally along geographical lines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/baseball/article/2017-10-06/di-baseball-championship-moves-16-seeds|publisher=NCAA|title=DI Baseball Championship moves to 16 seeds|date=October 6, 2017|accessdate=October 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Ballpark changes==\n* [[Boston College Eagles baseball|Boston College]] opened the new 1,000-seat [[Brighton Field]] on their Brighton campus.  The Eagles left their home of 57 years, [[Eddie Pellagrini Diamond at John Shea Field]] to create room for a new athletics field house.\n* The 2018 season was the last for [[Kentucky Wildcats baseball|Kentucky]] at [[Cliff Hagan Stadium]]. The Wildcats moved into the new [[Kentucky Proud Park]] for the 2019 season.\n* The 2018 season was also the last for [[UConn Huskies baseball|UConn]] at [[J. O. Christian Field]].  The Huskies will play elsewhere for 2019 while a new stadium is built.\n\n==Season outlook==\n:''For the full rankings, see [[2018 NCAA Division I baseball rankings]]''\n\n==Conference standings==\n{| cellpadding=\"5\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 American Athletic Conference baseball standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Atlantic Coast Conference baseball standings}} \n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Atlantic Sun Conference baseball standings}}\n|-\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Big East Conference baseball standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Big Ten Conference baseball standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Big 12 Conference baseball standings}}\n|-\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Big West Conference baseball standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Colonial Athletic Association baseball standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Conference USA baseball standings}}\n|-\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Mid-American Conference baseball standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Missouri Valley Conference baseball standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Mountain West Conference baseball standings}}\n|-\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Ohio Valley Conference baseball standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Pac-12 Conference baseball standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Southeastern Conference baseball standings}}\n|-\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Southern Conference baseball standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Southland Conference baseball standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Summit League baseball standings}}\n|-\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Sun Belt Conference baseball standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 West Coast Conference baseball standings}}\n|valign=\"top\" width=25em|{{2018 Western Athletic Conference baseball standings}}\n|}\n\n===Conference winners and tournaments===\nOf the 31 Division I [[List of NCAA conferences|athletic conferences]] that sponsor baseball, 29 end their [[regular season]]s with a [[single-elimination tournament]] or a [[double elimination tournament]]. The teams in each conference that win their regular season title are given the number one seed in each tournament. Two conferences, the Big West and Pac-12, do not hold a conference tournament. The winners of these tournaments, plus the Big West and Pac-12 regular-season champions, receive automatic invitations to the [[2018 NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Conference\n!Regular <br/> Season Winner\n!Conference <br/> Player of the Year\n!Conference <br/> Pitcher of the Year\n!Conference <br/> Coach of the Year\n!Conference <br/> Tournament\n!Tournament <br/> Venue \u2022 City\n!Tournament <br/> Winner\n|-\n| [[America East Conference]] || {{CBSB link|year=2018|team=Hartford Hawks|title=Hartford}} || Nick Campana, Hartford<ref name=\"AmEast awards\">{{cite press release|url=http://americaeast.com/news/2018/5/22/baseball-hartford-sweeps-major-awards-as-2018-aebase-all-conference-teams-announced.aspx |title=Hartford Sweeps Major Awards as 2018 #AEBASE All-Conference Teams Announced |publisher=America East Conference |date=May 22, 2018 |accessdate=June 1, 2018}}</ref> || Nicholas Dombkowski, Hartford<ref name=\"AmEast awards\"/>|| [[Justin Blood]], Hartford<ref name=\"AmEast awards\"/> || [[2018 America East Conference Baseball Tournament]] || [[Mahaney Diamond]] \u2022 [[Orono, Maine|Orono, ME]] || Hartford\n|-\n| [[American Athletic Conference]] || {{CBSB link|year=2018|team=Houston Cougars|title=Houston}} || Bryant Packard, {{CBSB link|year=2018|team=East Carolina Pirates|title=East Carolina}}<ref name=\"American awards\">{{cite press release|url=http://theamerican.org/news/20